mes © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Possibly an altered form of German <i>Köber</i> (see   Kober  ) or <i>Göber</i> (see   Gober  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Kober","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Bernhard, Angelika, Dieter, Ernst, Erwin, Gottlieb, Konrad, Manfred, Reinhold, Sepp, Wolfgang.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from a shortened derivative of the personal name <i>Jakob</i> (see   Jacob  ).","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from Middle High German <i>kober</i>, German <i>Kober</i> ‘basket’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a basket maker or perhaps a nickname for someone who carried a basket on his back."]}]},{"name":"Gérard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’ + <i>hard</i> ‘brave, hardy, strong’. In the later Middle Ages this was a more common name than   Gerald  , with which it was sometimes confused. Nowadays it is less common, surviving mainly among Roman Catholics, in honour of the many saints of this name."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerrard","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Gerard  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Jerrard","meanings":["Rare variant spelling of   Gerard  , probably influenced by the form of the modern surname, if not a transferred use."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Gérard Guillaume de Gavre knight was born in 1292, in Gavere, East Flanders, Belgium, his father, Rasse de Gavre, was 22 and his mother, Catherine de Mechelen, was 8. He married Yolande De Elsloo in 1314, in Belgium. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1330, in Belgium, at the age of 38."},"et":{"1292–1330":"1292–1330","1297–Male":"1297–Surnud","1293–Female":"1293–Surnud","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1318–1387":"1318–1387","1315–1400":"1315–1400","1322–Male":"1322–Surnud","1324–Female":"1324–Surnud","1271–1339":"1271–1339","1285–1320":"1285–1320","Aft 1320":"pärast 1320","1330":"1330","1297":"1297","1285":"1285","1271":"1271","1293":"1293","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","       1324":"1324","1315":"1315","1314":"1314","1324":"1324","1400":"1400","1322":"1322","       1322":"1322","1387":"1387","1320":"1320","1318":"1318","1339":"1339","Cambron-Casteau,Hainaut,Belgium":"Cambron-Casteau, Hainaut, Belgia","Belgium":"Belgia","Schorisse, East Flanders, Belgium":"Schorisse, Oost-Vlaanderen, Belgia","Cambron-Casteau, Hainaut (Henegouwen), Wallonie, België":"Cambron-Casteau, Hainaut, Belgia","Gavre, Flandre Orientale, Belgium":"Gavere, Oost-Vlaanderen, Belgia"},"fi":{"1292–1330":"1292–1330","1297–Male":"1297–Kuollut","1293–Female":"1293–Kuollut","1290–Female":"1290–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1318–1387":"1318–1387","1315–1400":"1315–1400","1322–Male":"1322–Kuollut","1324–Female":"1324–Kuollut","1271–1339":"1271–1339","1285–1320":"1285–1320","Aft 1320":"1320 jälkeen","1330":"1330","1297":"1297","1285":"1285","1271":"1271","1293":"1293","1292":"1292","1290":"1290